# Gradle Build Rules

## Structure

- Use `build.gradle.kts` (Kotlin DSL) or `build.gradle` consistently
- Keep `settings.gradle` minimal; use `gradle.properties` for version numbers
- Use the `java` and `com.github.johnrengelman.shadow` plugins for fat JARs

## Spigot Plugin Build

```groovy
// Use Paper/Spigot API as compileOnly
repositories {
    mavenCentral()
    maven { url = 'https://repo.papermc.io/repository/maven-public/' }
}
dependencies {
    compileOnly 'io.papermc.paper:paper-api:1.21-R0.1-SNAPSHOT'
}
```

## Best Practices

- Pin dependency versions in `build.gradle` or `gradle/libs.versions.toml`
- Use `compileOnly` for Spigot/Paper; never bundle server APIs
- Configure `shadowJar` to relocate shaded dependencies to avoid conflicts
- Set `sourceCompatibility` and `targetCompatibility` to match target server
- Add `-parameters` compiler arg for better reflection/debugging

## Tasks

- Use `./gradlew build` for standard build
- Use `./gradlew shadowJar` when shading dependencies
- Avoid committing `gradle/wrapper` JAR if using wrapper; commit `gradle-wrapper.properties`
